- **Sun Yat-sen** [[note 1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun_Yat-sen#cite_note-1)  ([/ˈsʌn ˌjætˈsɛn/](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Help:IPA/English) ; born **Sun Deming** ; 12 November 1866 – 12 March 1925)[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun_Yat-sen#cite_note-singtao1-2) [[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun_Yat-sen#cite_note-chron-nathall-3)  was a Chinese statesman, physician, and [political philosopher](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_philosopher) , who served as the provisional first president of the [Republic of China](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Republic_of_China_(1912%E2%80%931949) ) and the first leader of the [Kuomintang](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kuomintang)  (Nationalist Party of China). He is called the "[Father of the Nation](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Father_of_the_Nation) " in the Republic of China, and the "Forerunner of the Revolution" in the People's Republic of China for his instrumental role in the overthrow of the Qing dynasty during the [Xinhai Revolution](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xinhai_Revolution) . Sun is unique among 20th-century Chinese leaders for being widely revered in both [mainland China](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/People%27s_Republic_of_China)  and [Taiwan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Taiwan) .[[3]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sun_Yat-sen#cite_note-Tung1-4)
