- Narayan Meghaji Lokhande
    - ![](%LOCAL_FILE%Hag2ME-ybDscQ1JNQtmZgfnwblPPkrxuy7xwXbBtbyey0w1qRImI9TtcGy0nfGgtmKbWB3TpcaRKKbm88P2smHdCr6YGGRV8TG7VyfaMz5ZWp0TGulYoPkIKTG59yEe3.png)
    - Narayan Meghaji Lokhande was the father of trade union movement in  India. He is remembered not only for ameliorating the working  conditions of textile mill-hands in the 19th century but also for his  courageous initiatives on caste and communal issues.
    - Narayan Meghaji Lokhande was a prominent colleague of Mahatma Jotirao  Phule. He was born in a Mali family from Kanhersar in Pune district.[[3]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narayan_Meghaji_Lokhande#cite_note-3)   He had been educated up to high school. His wife's name was Gopikabai  and had a son named Gopinath. He learned of the Satyashodhak movement  early enough to become a member in its second year in 1874.[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narayan_Meghaji_Lokhande#cite_note-Lokhande-4)
    - Lokhande is acclaimed as the Father of the Trade Union Movement in India. From 1880 onwards he took over the management of  __ __  [ __Deenbandhu__ ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deenbandhu)  __ __    which was published from Mumbai. At this time he also quit his job as  head clerk in a cotton mill in Mumbai and founded Millhands'  Association, devoting himself fully to social service.[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narayan_Meghaji_Lokhande#cite_note-Lokhande-4)
    - Along with Lokhande, Phule also addressed the meetings of the  textile workers in Bombay. It is significant that before Phule and his  colleagues Krishnarao Bhalekar and Lokhande tried to organise the  peasants and the workers, no such attempt was made by any organisation  to redress their grievances.[[5]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narayan_Meghaji_Lokhande#cite_note-5) Lokhande started the first labour association in India — 'Bombay Mill Hands Association'.[[6]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narayan_Meghaji_Lokhande#cite_note-6)
