- Kesub Chanra Sen
    - ![](%LOCAL_FILE%l3HNyAinVhTtPmqJu98DF9c3DvRpeJgcQlYNdPeB3CsYK3UgNZuPSSQdNLpd1Vy0qxd2bn_oh0qzMjsEbB6b7aU-DcSILlw7OdF4AfcW50dKHOFMVeSQ0ZiZQAeQ-TGy.png)
    - 19 Nov 1838 - 8 Jan 1884
    - Hindu philosopher and social reformer
    - incorporate Christian theology within the framework of hindu thought
    - he became a member of the  [Brahmo Samaj](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brahmo_Samaj) in 1857[[1]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keshub_Chandra_Sen#cite_note-1) but established his own breakaway "Bharatvarshiya Brahmo Samaj" in 1866[[2]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keshub_Chandra_Sen#cite_note-2) while the Brahmo Samaj remained under the leadership of [Debendranath Tagore](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Debendranath_Tagore) (who headed the Brahmo Samaj till his death in 1905).[[3]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keshub_Chandra_Sen#cite_note-3)  In 1878 his followers abandoned him after the underage child marriage  of his daughter which exposed his campaign against child marriage as  hollow.[[4]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keshub_Chandra_Sen#cite_note-4) Later in his life he came under the influence of [Ramakrishna](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramakrishna) and founded a syncretic "New Dispensation"  inspired by [Christianity](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christianity), and  __ __ [ __Vaishnav__ ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vaishnav) __ __   __ __ [ __bhakti__ ](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhakti) __ __ , and Hindu practices.
